                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12612697" author="ryantxu" created="Fri, 11 Jul 2008 00:54:30 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Has anyone looked at this?  Any reason &lt;b&gt;not&lt;/b&gt; to default the jsp pages to UTF-8?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12612712" author="yseeley@gmail.com" created="Fri, 11 Jul 2008 01:32:23 +0100"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Any reason not to default the jsp pages to UTF-8?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We do want to default to UTF8, but we still sort of support Tomcat 5.5 with this release, which is only up to servlet spec 2.4 .  The comment suggests this API call suggests this is new for 2.5?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12612749" author="larsko" created="Fri, 11 Jul 2008 05:14:13 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The method setCharacterEncoding() is also part of the 2.4 servlet spec, I&apos;ve just tested it successfully with Tomcat 5.5.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, if everything is to be passed around as UTF-8, the Content-Type header of the pages should indicate this and the accept-charset of the forms should be set to UTF-8. I&apos;ve attached a path which makes the necessary changes.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12613092" author="yseeley@gmail.com" created="Sat, 12 Jul 2008 15:37:50 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I reproduced the problem... UTF8 work on Jetty (which nicely defaults to UTF-8) and does not work on Tomcat (on 5.5 at least).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12613094" author="yseeley@gmail.com" created="Sat, 12 Jul 2008 16:00:00 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I just committed this after testing with jetty &amp;amp; tomcat, firefox &amp;amp; IE.&lt;br/&gt;
Thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
